      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/?p=7385</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[I&#8217;ve been asked several times recently about choosing stocks in this type of market.  I&#8217;m going to do a  group response on the site rather than send individual emails.  Here goes. . . Here&#8217;s my suggestion:  in a streaky market &#8230; <a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/charts-data-analysis/charts-data-analysis-week-july-25th/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I&#8217;ve been asked several times recently about choosing stocks in this type of market.  I&#8217;m going to do a  group response on the site rather than send individual emails.  Here goes. . .</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s my suggestion:  in a streaky market (up one day and down the next) or in a  sideways market look for a stock with a potential for a quick profit.   Find a stock trading near support and plan to sell a portion of the position near resistance.</p>
<p>The best way, in my opinion, to find zones of support and resistance is by using my range lines method.  I look for stocks with at least $1.00 of potential profit.  Then I size my trades according to my risk parameters.</p>
<p>I place stops as soon as the order is filled.  I also place my sell order at the same time.  In essence I&#8217;ve bracketed my purchase price with two sell orders &#8212; one for 1/2 of the position a dime or so within my profit target and the second at my stop price in case the trade goes against me.</p>
<p>Once I&#8217;ve taken partial profits I keep moving the stop.  I don&#8217;t sell the remaining position until the stop is hit.  This has kept me in many trades that faltered a bit, but then went on to make stellar gains.</p>
<p>I hope that helped those of you who have written.  Now, on to the charts!</p>
<p>This S&amp;P chart is full of information.  The horizontal yellow lines are range resistance zones.  The market came up quickly through the first one, retraced and stopped at the same line that acted as support, and has just this week climbed past the second resistance zone.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-7386" href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/charts-data-analysis/charts-data-analysis-week-july-25th/attachment/sp-166/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-7386 aligncenter" title="S&amp;P" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/SP7-300x272.png" alt="" width="300" height="272" /></a></p>
<p>Those same horizontal yellow lines demonstrate the sideways trading motion going back to February.  This is what has given heartburn to so many investors and traders.  Within this range bound chart is a white arrow showing the market currently trading  up, but still within the range of consolidation.</p>
<p>The blue lines create a fork that splits the most recent high (July 6) and the most recent low (July 18).  This consolidating market will end when price trades above the highest yellow line and the top line of the fork.  Until it does so this market is a minefield of ticking time bombs waiting to explode.</p>
<p><span id="more-7385"></span>I&#8217;m still cautiously optimistic.  Here&#8217;s why &#8212; the junior averages are leading the charge.</p>
<p>The Composite is nearing old highs &#8211;</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-7387" href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/charts-data-analysis/charts-data-analysis-week-july-25th/attachment/nasdaq-51/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-7387 aligncenter" title="NASDAQ" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/NASDAQ3-300x259.png" alt="" width="300" height="259" /></a></p>
<p>and the NASDAQ 100 has broken to new highs.</p>
<p><a rel="attachment wp-att-7388" href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/charts-data-analysis/charts-data-analysis-week-july-25th/attachment/ndx-10/"><img class="size-medium wp-image-7388 aligncenter" title="NDX" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/NDX-300x273.png" alt="" width="300" height="273" /></a></p>
<p><strong>Sector Analysis</strong></p>
<p>Most of the sectors are trading within consolidation.  The Financials are very weak.  Energy looks good &#8212; the oil and gas sub-sector is within a few points of fresh highs.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s how the sectors did compared to the S&amp;P 500 which was up + 2% for the week just ended:</p>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Oil and Gas Exploration and Production  +4.9%</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Metals  3.8</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Energy  3.7</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Financails  3.1</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Technology  3.0</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Consumer Discretionary  1.9</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Utilities  1.3</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Consumer Staples  1.2</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Retail  1.2</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Health Care  1.1</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Materials  0.96</span></strong></address>
<address><strong><span style="color: #339966;">Industrials  0.79</span></strong></address>
<address>
</address>
<p><strong>Statistical Scans</strong></p>
<p>2% Daily</p>
<p>BAS,  CPX  FNSR  RES  URI</p>
<p>3% Weekly</p>
<p>BPI  BRY  COG  CPX  CVI  DDS  DRN  ROSE  TZOO</p>
<p>10% Weekly</p>
<p>AGQ  ARIA  ARUN  BAS  FNSR  TZOO</p>
<p>The Once A Week Trader</p>
<p>AG  ARIA  AUQ  CVI  EXPR  KEG  MPEL  PCYC  QCOR</p>
<p><strong>The Bottom Line:</strong></p>
<p>There is much angst in the headlines from the U.S. and around the world and plenty of reasons to be cautious.  Technically, the market is approaching a resistance zone and isn&#8217;t that far from old highs.  The charts don&#8217;t provide many set ups with the risk reward ratio I like.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m willing to be patient, play the cards I&#8217;m holding, and wait for the market to prove itself.</p>
<p>Stops are updated for the active trades.  Enjoy the weekend!</p>
