    <item>
      <title>Charts, Data, Analysis For The Week Of June 13th</title>
      <link>http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/uncategorized/charts-data-analysis-week/</link>
      <comments>http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/uncategorized/charts-data-analysis-week/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Sat, 11 Jun 2011 17:51:58 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>Range Trader</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[Current Market News]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[Stock Market]]></category>
      <category><![CDATA[Trading The Market]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/?p=7102</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[Friday&#8217;s ugly decline was not triggered by a particular event.  It was motivated sellers waiting to unload shares before the weekend as mentioned in this post. The four bellwether stocks:  AAPL (has done nothing and is below where it started &#8230; <a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/uncategorized/charts-data-analysis-week/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Friday&#8217;s ugly decline was not triggered by a particular event.  It was motivated sellers waiting to unload shares before the weekend as mentioned <a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/trading-the-market/market-trades-green/"><em><strong>in this post.</strong></em></a></p>
<p>The four bellwether stocks:  AAPL (has done nothing and is below where it started the year, yet it looks better than the other 3).</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/AAPL.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7103" title="AAPL" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/AAPL-300x258.png" alt="" width="300" height="258" /></a></p>
<p>FCX ( a grim death)</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/FCX.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7104" title="FCX" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/FCX-300x255.png" alt="" width="300" height="255" /></a></p>
<p>GOOG  (looks horrible)</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/GOOG.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7105" title="GOOG" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/GOOG-300x255.png" alt="" width="300" height="255" /></a></p>
<p>GS (very disappointing and can&#8217;t get out of its own  way).</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/GS.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7106" title="GS" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/GS-300x254.png" alt="" width="300" height="254" /></a></p>
<h2>This is a day to day market and this past week was horrible.  Where does  a market stop that has no mojo to the upside?  Logic tells us to watch  the next major moving average.  That would be the 200d MA which  registers 1262 on the S&amp;P 500.</h2>
<p>The NASDAQ Composite is at the 200, but . . .</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/NAZ.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7107" title="NAZ" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/NAZ-300x256.png" alt="" width="300" height="256" /></a></p>
<p>the NDX and RUT are 4 points above it.</p>
<p>The S&amp;P and DJ-30 are not at the 200d MA.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SP-5004.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7122" title="S&amp;P 500" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SP-5004-300x257.png" alt="" width="300" height="257" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>I can find the support levels, but I can&#8217;t predict where the market stops.  Stay flexible.  This market shows some definite flaws and there is likely more downside.  It looks like a bumpy ride until the end of the month and end of the quarter.</h3>
<p>Defense is on the field and trading capital should be cooling in the bank waiting for a better opportunity.</p>
<p><span id="more-7102"></span></p>
<p>A red week from top to bottom.  The S&amp;P was off -2.24 and the sectors stacked against the index like this:</p>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Utilities  -0.6</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Health Care  -1</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Staples  -1.2</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Materials  -1.2</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Industrials -2.4</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Financials  -2.5</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Energy  -2.5</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Discretionary  -2.7</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Technology  -3</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Oil and Gas  -3.2</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Retail  -3.4</span></address>
<address><span style="color: #ff0000;">Metals and Mining  -4</span></address>
<address> </address>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Not surprisingly, the statistical scans produced nothing to trade and nothing to watch.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h1>The market is extremely oversold.  The RSI is scraping the low 30&#8242;s and a 5,35 MACD is negative, too.  Remember, oscillators can stay oversold for a long time so they aren&#8217;t the best tool on which to base trading decisions.  I think these indicators are best for finding divergences.</h1>
<p>The weekly chart of the S&amp;P shows a clear hook in both of the above indicators.  And they both diverged from price.  The May 6th price high was higher than the price high made on February 18th.  But neither the RSI or the MACD confirmed that high.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SP-divergence.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7109" title="S&amp;P divergence" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SP-divergence-300x261.png" alt="" width="300" height="261" /></a></p>
<p>This market is consistently losing steam and can&#8217;t rally for more than a day.  It never breaks from being oversold.  That&#8217;s why it&#8217;s almost impossible to put on a short trade unless you&#8217;re willing to scalp for a dime here and there.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s a &#8220;tell&#8221; to watch for next week.  Best Buy (BBY) reports earnings.  This stock has been beaten like a drum.  Take note of their forward projections and how the stock trades post-earnings.</p>
<p>Have a good weekend and I&#8217;ll see you after the market close on Monday.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
      <wfw:commentRss>http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/uncategorized/charts-data-analysis-week/feed/</wfw:commentRss>
      <slash:comments>0</slash:comments>
    </item>
