    <item>
      <title>The Stock Market Trades Green!</title>
      <link>http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/trading-the-market/market-trades-green/</link>
      <comments>http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/trading-the-market/market-trades-green/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Fri, 10 Jun 2011 02:14:19 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>Range Trader</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Trading The Market]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/?p=7080</guid>
      <description><![CDATA[After a half dozen down days the stock market traded and closed green!  That&#8217;s a start, but it&#8217;s not tradeable, in my opinion. Undoubtedly, the lowest low risk area to go long will be when/if price travels to the 200d &#8230; <a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/trading-the-market/market-trades-green/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2>After a half dozen down days the stock market traded and closed green!  That&#8217;s a start, but it&#8217;s not tradeable, in my opinion.</h2>
<p>Undoubtedly, the lowest low risk area to go long will be when/if price travels to the 200d MA.</p>
<p>Price may never get there.  Remember the ride up starting in 2009?  That trend didn&#8217;t provide one easy entry for long buyers.  Just when you think a logical entry point is near the stock market does the unexpected.</p>
<p>The bearish fork is sending a signal, too.  Yet one bar is not enough proof on which to place a trade.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SP2.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-7081" title="S&amp;P" src="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/SP2-300x224.png" alt="" width="300" height="224" /></a></p>
<p><span id="more-7080"></span>Alan Andrews, creator of the Median Line study, had a rule that sticks in my mind.  He noted that when price declines (or increases) to the median line without touching it expect a reversal.  The reversal should be larger than the prior swing.</p>
<p>Is that the situation on tonight&#8217;s chart?  I&#8217;m willing to give it a day or two.  Price can still decline a bit more without touching the median line.</p>
<h3>Lots of chop in this stock market and it&#8217;s no fun to get chewed up and spit out by a jerky tape.  Let&#8217;s see if the bulls have more punch and can turn the tide or if they&#8217;re fearful of holding positions over the weekend.</h3>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="http://www.rangetraders.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/EBIX.png"><br />
</a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
